Each year in the United States, more than $200 billion is spent on food that is never consumed. Fifty million tons of this uneaten food ends up in landfills, while more than 48 million American families—one in seven—live in food-insecure households. The resources used to grow, process, and transport food are all squandered when uneaten foods are disposed of. That’s why my office hosted a round table discussion on Friday, Feb. 17th with community leaders to address issues surrounding food waste and encourage innovative ways to fight hunger.  I thank all who participated and look forward to working with you in the future.

I am deeply concerned about recent bomb threats on the Mandel Jewish Community Center and on Jewish community centers (JCCs) nationwide. As a community and nation, we must continue to spread a message of peace, hope, and love, not hate and divisiveness. Threats on our nation’s JCCs cannot continue. They must end now!

Over the past two days, I attended two events with leaders of #OH11 Muslim communities at Masjid Bilal and First Cleveland Mosque.  I am proud to stand with them and will continue to do so.  Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. said, “There comes a time when silence becomes betrayal.” I will not betray the Muslim community. I strongly oppose President Donald Trump’s Muslim ban and will continue to advocate against it.  I thank the Imams for inviting me and all who worked to make these events happen.

Today, Congresswoman Marcia L. Fudge (OH-11) spoke to more than 500 constituents at her first town hall meeting of 2017.  Topics highlighted included updates from the Trump Administration; concerns about the Affordable Care Act, Medicare, and Medicaid; the need for equitable access to quality public education; and issues surrounding immigration and civil liberties. The Congresswoman urged attendees to stay engaged in the policy process and re-affirmed her commitment to speaking on their behalf in Washington.

Drug abuse is taking a devastating toll on our communities. We must do everything we can to stop it. Today, I learned we lost 60 Cuyahoga County residents due to heroin, opioid and fentanyl abuse this February. Earlier last month, I joined Congressman Mike Turner (OH-10) and Congresswoman Niki Tsongas (MA-3) to introduce TREAT Act.  This bill aims to expand access to substance abuse treatment in prisons. In addition, I will re-introduce The Breaking Addiction Act, to allow States to apply for waivers and increase the number of drug abuse patients that can be served through Medicaid. We all play a role in combating drug abuse and reversing the effects of these deadly substances in our communities. Talking is not enough. http://www.cleveland.com/metro/index.ssf/2017/03/cuyahoga_county_hits_record_nu.html

Pi is a useful mathematical symbol (and value) in geometry.  It is the ratio of a circle’s circumference to its diameter. Pi is a constant number, meaning that for all circles of any size, Pi will be the same. In 2009, the House passed a resolution supporting March 14th as National Pi Day. Pi is just one example of the interesting topics and symbols to be discussed this week at my NEO STREAM conference. Click here https://fudge.house.gov/neo-stream-conference-2017/ to learn more and join me in recognizing Pi Day! How do you celebrate? #NEOSTREAM2017

This National Public Health Week (#NPHW), I‘m focused on how we can improve the health of all Americans. Step One? #ProtectOurCare.  #TrumpCare would have kicked 24 million off health care, and raised premiums and out-of-pocket costs for hardworking Americans. Medicaid would have been devastated. Kids would have been left without services as fundamental as speech therapy. Seniors would have paid premiums five times higher than what others pay ... It’s time for Republicans to take a stand for progress and work *with* Democrats to improve our current health care system instead of ripping it to shreds. Join me in recognizing #NPHW by sharing this message and advocating for better care for everyone!

Today is Equal Pay Day, which marks all the extra months that women have to work into this year – just to catch up to the average man’s earnings last year.  Equal pay for equal work is a fundamental principle of fairness in our economy and in our democracy.  Republicans should work with Democrats to ensure that women and working families receive the fair pay and the bigger paychecks needed to keep America moving forward. Pass the #PaycheckFairnessAct
Equal Pay Day is not over, and neither is the purpose of our advocacy! Today, and every day, I urge my Congressional colleagues to pass policies that promote pay equity for all!

ATTN OH 11 HIGH SCHOOL SOPHOMORES & JUNIORS!!! APPLY TO THE CBCF SPOUSES ESSAY CONTEST!!! Each year the Spouses of the Congressional Black Caucus Members partner with CBCF to volunteer and dedicate their time and talents to creating educational opportunities to prepare our future leaders.  Students are presented with a topic that embodies some of our communities’ most pressing issues and are asked to write an essay to defend their research, analyses, and opinion. This year’s topic is "The Legacy of Entrepreneurship in African-American Communities." Winners and their families are invited to Washington, DC in September to accept their awards and attend a panel discussion on the topic during the CBCF 47th Annual Legislative Conference. All written essay submissions are due via http://bit.ly/2017essaycontest by Friday, April 21, 2017. Share this message and apply today!

I am pleased to congratulate Mary Frances McGowan, a former District Office intern, who was recently awarded the 2017 NBC / John Carroll University “Meet the Press” Fellowship. While working with my office, Mary Frances always presented fresh ideas and content. She brought a ‘can-do’ attitude to her work and was an asset to my Communications staff. I wish her well in her future endeavors!  The Fellowship was created in 2009 in memory of the Sunday morning program’s legendary host, Tim Russert, a 1972 graduate of John Carroll. It is awarded annually to a John Carroll graduating senior who plans to pursue a career in political journalism. The Fellowship is a nine-month position at NBC’s “Meet the Press.”   http://sites.jcu.edu/newsroom/2017/05/10/mary-frances-mcgowan-named-recipient-prestigious-nbc-jcu-meet-press-fellowship/

#OH11 Mark Your Calendars: The 1st Annual Breaking Down Barriers Hiring Event will take place on Friday, June 9th. The fair is open to job seekers with significant legal barriers to employment. Hosted at Tri-C’s Metro campus, the event will feature community resources to expunge or seal one’s record, Work Opportunity Tax Credits, Federal CQE, and employment services, as well as, employers willing to accept applications on spot. A pre-event workshop will also be provided to help attendees get prepared. To rsvp, visit https://www.cognitoforms.com/BDB8/Register. For more information, contact (216) 881-5440 or email breakingdownbarriersinitiative@gmail.com.

Last week, the U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) launched a new online tool to help veterans with PTSD called the PTSD Treatment Decision Aid. It helps educate patients about effective treatment options for PTSD and encourages them to participate actively in decisions about their care.    The tool includes information about evidence-based PTSD treatments, such as talk therapy and prescription medication options. It also includes useful information designed for people who have served in the military. Click here to learn more: https://www.ptsd.va.gov/apps/Decisionaid/

Though President Lincoln's Emancipation Proclamation freed many slaves in 1863, the Executive Order had little effect in Texas. Millions of slaves remained in bondage. Therefore #‎Juneteenth‬ is celebrated each year to commemorate the day millions of slaves in Galveston, Texas were told they were finally free in 1865. Join me in remembering the lives lost during one of the darkest periods in the history of our nation and in taking steps toward healing and civil rights for all.

I joined nearly 200 Members of Congress in filing a federal lawsuit against President Trump for violating one of the Constitution’s critical anti-corruption provisions: the Foreign Emoluments Clause.  The emoluments clause prohibits the President from accepting foreign payments without seeking and receiving Congressional authorization. President Trump’s refusal to disclose or seek Congress’s authorization for his sprawling foreign financial interests is a brazen violation of the Constitution and a danger to our democracy itself.  I will use every tool I have to hold this President accountable to the Constitution and to the American people. https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/14/us/politics/democrats-in-congress-to-sue-trump-over-foreign-business-dealings.html?smid=tw-share

Cleft lip and cleft palate occur when a baby’s lip or mouth does not form properly during pregnancy. Each year in the United States, 2,650 babies are born with a cleft palate and 4,400 babies are born with a cleft lip. Isolated orofacial clefts are one of the most common types of birth defects in the United States. Learn more about cleft and craniofacial problems here https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/birthdefects/cleftlip.html

Ohio and the nation are in the middle of a deadly epidemic. Opioids, heroin, and fentanyl have claimed thousands of lives throughout our State and the 11th Congressional District. All too often, those who seek care are turned away because our communities cannot meet the demand for care. While I support the Administration’s decision to focus on the opioid crisis, more can be done to provide greater access to treatment.  I urge my colleagues and the Administration to support my bill, the Breaking Addiction Act of 2017, to eliminate the Institutions for Mental Diseases (IMD) exclusion. The Breaking Addiction Act would permit states to provide care for those suffering from addiction at certain treatment facilities with more than 16 beds. Every minute we restrict access to treatment is another minute a life is at risk. Eliminating this antiquated provision will cut through unnecessary red tape, increase access to treatment, and give states the flexibility they need to save lives.  https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/26/us/politics/trump-opioid-crisis.html?_r=0

Millions of America’s children and families were put at risk when CHIP and Community Health Center programs were allowed to expire 34 days ago. That is 34 days of uncertainty for nearly nine million children and health care providers across the country.    Unfortunately, the CHAMPION Act is another veiled attempt to sabotage the Affordable Care Act. The bill cuts $6.35 billion from the ACA’s Prevention Fund, putting vaccines, chronic care, and emergency preparedness at risk. It also shortens the grace period for paying ACA Marketplace premiums from 90 days to 30 days, hurting the most vulnerable who may be struggling to make a payment. We should support Americans experiencing hardship, not kick them while their down.  Congressional Republicans chose to use our nation’s children and most vulnerable communities as bargaining chips, rather than work with Democrats to increase access to health care for all Americans.  I could not in good conscience vote for such a heartless bill when more than 223,000 Ohio children receive coverage under CHIP, and Community Health Centers in the 11th Congressional District provide affordable health care services to 85,786 Ohioans. Americans deserve better.  https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/house-chip-no-closer-political-games_us_59fc8b8be4b0b0c7fa39c75b

Today I voted no on yet another short-term, stop-gap funding measure. This Continuing Resolution provides only temporary relief for the nearly nine million children depending on the Children’s Health Insurance Program (CHIP) and health care providers working tirelessly at our Community Health Centers.  House Republicans wasted another opportunity to work with Democrats in a bipartisan way on behalf of millions of children and their families.  I would have supported a bill that addressed the needs of the hardworking Americans that sent us to Congress; a bill that provided stable reauthorization and funding for CHIP and Community Health Centers, funding to combat the opioid epidemic, stabilized the health insurance marketplace, protected DREAMers, and addressed the pension crisis.  Today, House Republicans also put forth a supplemental disaster relief funding package that does nothing to guarantee help for our fellow Americans in Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands. This is a bill the Senate is not expected to consider until 2018. People without homes or electricity in Puerto Rico, the U.S. Virgin Islands, Texas, Florida, and California cannot wait. Rather than spending valuable time passing a tax cut that predominately benefits the wealthiest Americans, we should have been working to protect sick children and disaster victims. We should be voting on things that will affect people’s lives now.  https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/after-passing-tax-overhaul-gop-returns-to-infighting-as-shutdown-deadline-looms/2017/12/21/dfad1890-e659-11e7-ab50-621fe0588340_story.html?utm_term=.731811653f2d

A Different World: Exerting Power to Effect Change  The legislative and political climate in America has changed.  Hate speech is everywhere. Polarization has become commonplace. And, collaboration and compromise has given way to partisanship. Voting Rights, healthcare, public education, women’s rights, and many other issues which affect the lives of all Americans are under attack. Communities of color stand to suffer the most.   Organizations across the country are coming together to be a part of #theresistance movement.  The 2017 National Pan-Hellenic Council Presidents’ forum will discuss ‘out of the box’ strategies for NPHC organizations to mobilize and engage their membership to start, continue, or strengthen a movement to change the current legislative, judicial and executive landscape at all levels of government.  It is time for the NPHC to take the lead and exert their power both individually and collectively in the governance arena.  This timely conversation will allow members of the “Divine Nine” to hear from their organizations’ leadership, take away resources and tools,  and get their marching orders for the years to come.   It is ‘a different world’ and we must develop new strategies to help our communities survive and succeed.
